	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Fiscal cost of Côte d’Ivoire IEPA is modest</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The World Bank has published a Trade Policy Note, ‘Estimating the cost of the Côte d’Ivoire-EU Economic Partnership Agreement’. The Bank’s simulation concludes that the tariff liberalisation that the Côte d’Ivoire must undertake under the Interim EPA (IEPA) will result in a loss over a 15-year period of equivalent to 2.2% of total government revenue in 2007. Although this amounts to around CFAfr43 billion in absolute terms, the study anticipates that a part of this loss will be offset by a rise in import volumes as the economy grows. The analysis uses actual transaction level data for 2007 from customs covering all imports (apart from those going into warehouses or imported by government) as well as the excise taxes and the value-added tax collected at the border on imports.</p><p>The revenue effects of the IEPA might have been expected to be particularly high in Côte d’Ivoire because a high proportion of its non-oil imports (50.4%) originate in the EU, and hence are covered by the liberalisation. But the study found that imports from the EU already faced generally lower tariffs prior to the IEPA than did those from the rest of the world, apart from ECOWAS (with trade-weighted applied tariff rates of 5.3% and 7.5% respectively). Accordingly, the country derived in 2007 only 39% of its customs revenue from imports originating in the EU.</p><p>Using the World Bank’s Tariff Reform Impact Simulation Tool (TRIST), the analysis measures both the reduction of tariffs on goods currently imported from the EU and the effect of trade diversion (whereby goods currently imported from another source are in future purchased from Europe in order to obtain the benefit of the lower IEPA tariffs). What the simulation tool cannot do is take any account of the effects of changes to the level of growth (whether as a result of the IEPA or any other factor) on the total volume of imports. The study assumes that these will rise and that this will partly offset the IEPA-induced losses.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank, ‘Estimating the fiscal impact of the Côte d’Ivoire-EU EPA’, <i>Africa Trade Policy Notes</i>, Note no. 4, August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRREGTOPTRADE/Resources/4_CI_TRIST_Policy_Note_FINAL.pdf" target="_self">http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRREGTOPTRADE/Resources/4_CI_TRIS...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>An inevitable consequence of liberalising ‘substantially all trade’, as is being done in the (I)EPAs, is that countries will lose ‘substantially all their revenue’ derived from taxes imposed on imports from their partners. Since tariffs and the like are only one form of consumer tax they can be replaced in principle by others, mitigating the fiscal consequences, but this is not a straightforward exercise. There are technical obstacles: tariffs are ubiquitous in developing countries precisely because they are one of the easiest taxes to collect; the alternatives are more costly and more likely to be evaded. There are also political obstacles: if markets are competitive post-tax, prices of some goods will go down but those on others will go up; consumers rarely give politicians credit for tax cuts, and only blame for offsetting tax increases – and if markets are not competitive, the latter may exceed the former.</p><p>The extent to which these challenges can be overcome depends critically on the relative scale of the revenue loss from liberalisation. A relatively small loss phased in over a long period will give plenty of time for alternatives to be put in place. This is something that has rarely been calculated for the (I)EPAs since it requires details that are rarely published: for example, how much tax was actually collected on the goods subject to liberalisation prior to the IEPA? The World Bank study, while it applies on just one IEPA, is a very valuable contribution to this task – and needs to be replicated in all (I)EPA signatory countries.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
